sub.name: Luminance
sub.unit: The candela is the luminous intensity, in a given direction, of a source that emits monochromatic radiation of frequency 540E+12 hertz and that has a radiant intensity in that direction of 1/683 watt per steradian (16th CGPM, Conférence Générale des Poids et Mesures, 1979)
The exact conversion factor is 1E+04/pi

sub.name: Electric Potential
sub.unit: Named for the Italian physicist Alessandro Volta

sub.name: Electric Current
sub.unit: The ampere is the constant current in two straight conductors, which have infinite length and negligible circular cross section, parallel to each other and placed 1 meter apart in vacuum, and produce a force equal to 2E-07 newton per meter of length (9th CGPM, Conférence Générale des Poids et Mesures, 1948)

sub.name: Radioactivity
sub.unit: Named for Antoine Henri Becquerel, a French Nobel prize winner (1903). Activation of nucleus disintegration. One becauerel is defined as the number of radial rays spontaneously emitted by a radioactive substance in one second, not proportional to radial energy or danger

sub.name: Dose Equivalent
sub.unit: Named for the Swedish physicist Rolf Maximilliam Sievert. Used to measure biological effect by radiation and expresses a degree of danger against human body

sub.name: Absorbed Dose
sub.unit: Named for the English physicist Stephen Gray. An SI unit which expresses energy received by a substance irradiated with ionized radiation
